<IN>
BOND MARKET NEWS (BON)
MORTGAGES, MORTGAGE BANKERS, MORTGAGE-BACKED SECURITIES (MOR)
</IN>
<LP>
   The following were among yesterday's offerings and
pricings in U.S. and non-U.S. capital markets, with terms and
syndicate manager, as compiled by Dow Jones Capital Markets
Report:
                                                                                                       

                         CORPORATES
                                                                                                       

</LP>
<TEXT>
   Student Loan Marketing Association -- $150 million of
notes, due May 24, 1994, priced at par for an initial yield
9.375%. The notes, which are noncallable for two years, will
be reoffered at various prices through underwriters led by
Merrill Lynch Capital Markets. The notes were priced at a
spread of 34 basis points above the Treasury's four-year
note.
                                                                                                       

                         MUNCIPALS
                                                                                                       

   Ohio Water Development Authority -- $67.3 million of
Series A and Ohio Air Quality Development Authority's Series
B State of Ohio collateralized pollution control revenue
refunding bonds, Toledo Edison Company Project, due May 15,
2019, were tentatively priced by a Shearson Lehman Hutton
Inc. group to yield 8.25% in 2019.Series A consists of a
single portion of $33.2 million bonds priced as 8% securities
at 97.26 to yield 8.25% in 2019. Series B consists of a
single portion of $34.1 million bonds priced as 8% securities
at 97.26 to yield 8.25% in 2019. The bonds are rated Baa by
Moody's and triple-B by S&amp;P.
                                                                                                       

                         MORTGAGES
                                                                                                       

   Federal Home Loan Mortgage Corp. -- $520 million of Remic
mortgage securities is being offered in 15 classes by
Prudential-Bache Securities Inc. The offering, Series 172, is
backed by Freddie Mac 9 1/2% securities with a weighted
average remaining term to maturity of 29.4 years. The yields,
where available, range from 9.59% to 10.88%.
   Federal National Mortgage Association -- A $500 million
issue of Remic mortgage securities is being offered in nine
classes by Salomon Brothers Inc. The offering, Series
1990-64, is backed by Fannie Mae 10% securities. The "L"
class is eligble for thrift liquidity purposes.
   Federal Home Loan Mortgage Corp. -- $416 million of Remic
mortgage securities, offered in nine classes by Shearson
Lehman Hutton Inc. The offering, Series 171, and backed by
Freddie Mac 9% securities, with a weighted average coupon
rate of 9.97%.
   Federal National Mortgage Association -- $300 million of
Remic mortgage securities, offered in nine classes by Morgan
Stanley &amp; Co. The offering, Series 1990-62, is backed by
Fannie Mae 9% securities. The floater and inverse floater are
pegged to the one-month London Interbank offered rate. A
Morgan Stanley official said the TAC classes are structured
the same way as the original TAC classes in the derivative
market. That means they offer investors call protection if
rates fall but extend in average life if rates rise and
prepayments slow. There are no spreads available on the
issue, but the spreads are tighter than those on straight
Remic classes but wider than those on prepayment-protected
PAC classes. The collateral consists of Fannie Mae 9s with an
underlying weighted average coupon rate of 9.65% and a
weighted average remaining term to maturity of 29.5 years.
   Federal National Mortgage Association -- $300 million of
Remic mortgage securities, offered in nine classes by J.P.
Morgan Securities Inc. The offering, Series 1990-63, is
backed by Fannie Mae 9 1/2% securities.
                                                                                                       

                         EUROBONDS
                                                                                                       

   European Investment Bank (Agency) -- 200 million European
currency units of 10% fungible Eurobonds due Feb. 14, 1997,
priced at 99.61 via lead manager Banco di Roma. Fungible with
800 million ECU issue outstanding.
   Compagnie Bancaire -- 600 million French francs of 10 1/4%
Eurobonds due June 10, 1992, priced at 101.10 to yield
10.26%, via Credit Commercial de France.
   Commonwealth Bank of Australia (Australia) -- $100 million
(Australian) of 15 1/2% bonds due June 7, 1993, priced at 102
to yield 15.28%, via Hambros Bank Ltd. Guaranteed by the
Commonwealth of Australia.
   Merrill Lynch &amp; Co. Inc. (U.S.) -- 100 million Deutsche
marks of zero-coupon bonds due May 18, 2000, priced at 43.75
to yield 9.26% on an all-in basis excluding expenses, via
Merrill Lynch AG.
   General Electric Capital Corp. (U.S.) -- $200 million of 9
5/8% Eurobonds due Nov. 17, 1994, priced at 101 3/8, via
Kidder Peabody International.
   SBC Luxembourg (Swiss parent) -- 100 million Swiss francs
of 8% privately placed notes due June 1, priced at 100 1/4,
via Swiss Bank Corp.
</TEXT>
