<HL>
   Farah Inc. Is Sued
   By Largest Holder,
   Its Ex-Chairman
   ----
   By Alfredo Corchado
   Staff Reporter of The Wall Street Journal
</HL>
<DATE>
05/04/90
</DATE>
<SO>
WALL STREET JOURNAL (J), PAGE C5
</SO>
<CO>
   FRA
</CO>
<LP>
   EL PASO, Texas -- William F. Farah, who was removed as
chairman of Farah Inc. last week, sued the company, Farah
directors and top officers to prevent them from cutting him
off from the clothing manufacturer he helped manage for 53
years.
   Mr. Farah, a company director and the company's largest
stockholder with one million shares, or about a 15% stake, is
asking an El Paso county court for a temporary restraining
order to keep other board members and Farah's top management
from restricting his role as a board member and company
consultant.
</LP>
<TEXT>
   Calling his fellow board members "spiteful conspirators"
who want to destroy him financially, Mr. Farah charges that
board members have threatened to terminate his three-year
consulting services contract. That contract, which has two
years remaining, pays him an annual fee of $365,000 and
provides Mr. Farah with an office and secretary. According to
a letter attached to the lawsuit, the board unanimously
decided at a March 13 meeting that Mr. Farah and his
secretary would vacate the premises by May 1.
   Mr. Farah resigned as president and chief executive
officer of the company last year and was succeeded by Richard
C. Allender.
   Mr. Farah wasn't available for comment yesterday.
   Last week, the board removed Mr. Farah as chairman after
he apparently wrote letters to directors urging them to
either replace current management or resign. Mr. Farah is
said to be unhappy with the direction of the company. He was
succeeded by Thomas G. Wyman, a recently elected board member
who has a 5% stake in Farah.
   In an interview conducted before the suit was filed, Mr.
Allender declined to discuss the company's relationship with
Mr. Farah. But when asked about Mr. Farah's pending lawsuit,
Mr. Allender said: "I can't afford to be concerned about what
Willie {Mr. Farah} may or may not do. I have a business to
run."
   According to the lawsuit, Messrs. Allender and Wyman
interpreted Mr. Farah's consulting contract to mean that Mr.
Farah should provide advice only when Mr. Allender requests
it.
   In a letter to Mr. Allender filed with court documents,
Mr. Farah said he would be "derelict in my duty if, as you
suggest, I limit my efforts, inquiries and activities to mere
attendance of board meetings."
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>
WSJ900504-0156
</DOCNO>
<DOCID>
900504-0156.
</DOCID>
<HL>
   Recycling Waste Is Gaining Popularity
   Among Americans, Group's Poll Shows
   ----
   By Bill Paul
   Staff Reporter of The Wall Street Journal
</HL>
<DATE>
05/04/90
</DATE>
<SO>
WALL STREET JOURNAL (J), PAGE B3B
</SO>
<IN>
ENVIRONMENT (ENV)
CHEMICALS, PLASTICS (CHM)
PULP, PAPER, PACKAGING (ALL TYPES) (PUL)
ALUMINUM (ALU)
NON-FERROUS METALS (ONF)
PETROLEUM (PET)
</IN>
<LP>
   ATLANTA -- Recycling's popularity is soaring.
   Three out of four Americans believe they could more than
double the amount of waste they presently recycle, compared
with just 40% who thought so last July, according to a poll
released yesterday by the National Solid Wastes Management
Association, a Washington, D.C., trade group.
</LP>
<TEXT>
   Only 11% of the U.S.'s 160 million tons a year of
municipal solid waste is currently recycled, and even that
much is straining municipal officials, who must find somebody
to buy all those old newspapers, glass bottles, aluminum cans
and plastic containers.
   Nevertheless, 74% of those polled in March believe they
could beat the federal Environmental Protection Agency's
long-term goal of recycling 25% of the U.S.'s municipal solid
waste. And one in four said they could recycle as much as
three-fourths of everything they now throw out, compared with
just one in 10 who thought so last summer.
   To be sure, the public's sharply growing commitment to
recycling is already reflected in some states' recycling
goals. California and Iowa want to recycle 50% of their
garbage by the year 2000. New York wants to hit 50% by 1997,
Washington state by 1995 and Maine by 1994.
   But while there aren't yet enough new products and markets
to absorb the growing amount of recycled items being
collected by communities, experts attending the waste
association's annual convention here agreed that U.S.
manufacturers are going to be under increased public pressure
to use more recycled raw material in the goods they produce.
The industries most likely to be affected, the experts said,
are plastics, paper, glass, rubber, aluminum, metals and oil.
   The good news for manufacturers is that, "The public is
prepared to pay more" for those goods if they contain a lot
of recycled material, said Allen Moore, president of the
waste association.
   Newspaper and magazine publishers will be especially
affected, according to a study that was also released
yesterday by the association. The study found that while U.S.
newspapers contained only about 9% recycled fiber in 1988,
they will have 16% by 1992, 25% by 1995 and 40% by the year
2000 -- in part because of a proliferation of state
regulations requiring more recycled-fiber content in
newspapers.
   Moreover, the study noted that in order for publishers to
get the quality of newsprint they need, old magazine fiber
will have to be blended with old newspaper fiber, meaning
that, before long, Americans can expect to start putting
their magazines at the curb as well.
   The poll also found that public opposition to garbage
incinerators continues to lessen. Indeed, more than half of
those polled (55%) said they wouldn't object to an
incinerator being built in their community, compared with 44%
who didn't object last summer, and only 39% in February 1989.
   Even landfills got a bit more public support this time
around. Some 36% of those polled said they wouldn't object to
a new landfill in their community, compared with just 23% who
didn't object last summer and 30% in February 1989. A solid
59% majority, however, said they would still object, with
only 5% holding no opinion.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>
WSJ900504-0155
</DOCNO>
<DOCID>
900504-0155.
</DOCID>
<HL>
   First Brands Posts
   83% Drop in Net
   For Its 3rd Period
   ----
   By Udayan Gupta
   Staff Reporter of The Wall Street Journal
</HL>
<DATE>
05/04/90
</DATE>
<SO>
WALL STREET JOURNAL (J), PAGE A5A
</SO>
<CO>
   FBR
</CO>
<IN>
EARNINGS (ERN)
ENVIRONMENT (ENV)
</IN>
<GV>
FEDERAL TRADE COMMISSION (FTC)
</GV>
<LP>
   DANBURY, Conn. -- First Brands Corp. reported an 83%
decline in profit for its fiscal third quarter and warned
that earnings for its year ending June 30 could be lower than
expected.
   The manufacturer of such consumer brands as Glad, Prestone
and STP, cited difficulties in its antifreeze business.
Fiscal 1990 per-share profit "may be slightly lower than
expectations of $2.50," compared with the year-earlier $1.97,
when profit totaled $61 million.
</LP>
<TEXT>
   Profit for the third quarter, ended March 31, fell to $2.7
million, or 12 cents a share, from $16.1 million, or 80 cents
a share, a year earlier. Revenue fell 17% to $221.3 million
from $267.5 million.
   Fiscal 1989 figures included $20.7 million in revenue from
the company's European businesses, which have since been
sold, the company said. Adjusting for the sale, quarterly
profit rose fivefold to $3.5 million, or 16 cents a share,
from $693,000 or three cents a share. Revenue fell 10% to
$221.3 million from $246.8 million.
   First Brands said that lower-than-expected antifreeze
sales, primarily caused by price uncertainty, had reduced
overall sales below the prior year and plan. And because
there were added pressures to reduce antifreeze prices
further, it expected profit margins for the rest of the year
to be lower as well.
   In addition to its problems with antifreeze, First Brands
also has been facing criticism over the environmental claims
the company has made about some of its products. It also has
had problems with one new-product introduction.
   The Federal Trade Commission and several state attorneys
general have been investigating claims by First Brands and
other plastic manufacturers that their products are
degradable and therefore better for the environment. The
inquiries have had no business impact and aren't expected to
have any such impact in the future, said Donald DeSantis,
vice president and chief financial officer.
   Earlier this year, First Brands recalled 200,000 cans of a
new car-wax product, after receiving three reports that cans
ruptured after being weakened from the inside by corrosion.
The product, Simoniz Quick Gloss, which retails for $4, is a
spray-on shine for use at auto shows and in showrooms. The
product accounts for a very small portion of sales and hasn't
affected revenue, Mr. DeSantis said.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
