<HL>
   LEISURE &amp; ARTS -- On Sports:
   Pitching Winners for the Derby
   ----
   By Frederick C. Klein
</HL>
<DATE>
05/04/90
</DATE>
<SO>
WALL STREET JOURNAL (J), PAGE A9
</SO>
<LP>
   Kentucky Derby Day is upon us again, and I suppose you'd
like to know who's going to win. Look no further; the pitcher
is in focus.
   "I like Unbridled," says the pitcher, Rob Murphy of the
Boston Red Sox. "I base the pick mostly on breeding -- he's
the only colt in the field who got a `yes' on my rating
system as a yearling -- but he's also a late runner in a
field with a lot of early speed. Plus, you should get a good
price on him."
</LP>
<TEXT>
   Now, you well may ask why Murphy, a dark-haired,
left-handed reliever of imposing stuff and mien, has been
summoned from the bullpen as a horse-racing expert. The
answer is because he is one. When he's not setting up saves
for Lee Smith or Jeff Reardon, he's exercising his computer,
seeking likely prospects for the horse-buying partnerships he
forms and manages.
   His company, M375 Thoroughbreds, is doing quite nicely,
thanks. In business since 1984, it currently has shares in
four racing animals, three unraced two-year-olds, three
broodmares and six yearlings or sucklings. All four runners
have recorded victories, and their combined winnings of about
$200,000 have almost doubled their purchase prices.
   And that could be just the start. "We've been limited by
the money at our disposal, but this fall we plan to be more
ambitious," says Rob. "I might put together a players' group,
and I certainly intend to get involved more heavily myself.
   "In case you haven't heard," he adds with a wink,
"ballplayers make pretty good money these days."
   The husky, 29-year-old Murphy is in that category, having
inked a contract that will pay him a total of $1.85 million
for this season and next. He qualified for that princely sum
by being the Major Leagues' busiest hurler over the past
three campaigns in terms of appearances (237), and by
inducing most of batters he faced to retire without much
fuss.
   The log for Murphy's four years in the Bigs -- three with
the Cincinnati Reds and one with Boston -- shows an earned
run average of 2.65 and 317 strikeouts in 344 innings. He's
putting them out in style again this term, with 19 K's in 16
innings through Tuesday.
   Unlike some play-for-payers, though, Murphy knows that
muscular heroics won't last, and this is where his horse
business comes in. It's perhaps no wonder that he's attracted
to the breeding end of the turf sport, because he has been
bred for it himself. His maternal grandfather, Frank Ashley,
was a well-known race announcer, and his grandma, Rose
LeDuke, kept charts for the Daily Racing Form. His father's
stepfather, Fred Smith, was a top jockey during the 1940s.
His dad, Bob, a building contractor, raises and races horses
out of his Early Morning Farm in Ocala, Fla.
   "We were a typical American family, except that we spent
all our holidays at the track," the pitcher recalls.
   Murphy got plugged into computers as a high schooler in
his native Miami, and learned early on that he could combine
his interests profitably. He and a friend designed a
handicapping program for a computer class, and got an "A" by
correctly picking Affirmed, Alydar and Believe It to finish
1-2-3 in the 1978 Kentucky Derby. Affirmed turned out to be a
great horse, so hindsight might adjudge the feat
unremarkable. But Affirmed was the second betting choice to
Alydar on Derby Day, and Believe It went off at 7-to-1.
   Murphy continued his computer studies at the U.'s of
Florida and Kentucky, but stowed his racing yen because he
was happily mowing 'em down on the diamonds. He revived it in
1983 after three so-so seasons of Class A ball in the Reds'
chain seemed to have dead-ended his career. That was partly
because a minor-league coach, who shall be unnamed, decided
that the game needed a 6-foot-2, 215-pound knuckleballer, and
induced Murphy to adopt the erratic pitch.
   "It was either my having a great spring in '84, or finding
something else to do," Rob says. "I figured I needed an
alternate plan."
   So he sat himself down before a computer and plumbed
racing's voluminous breeding stats, seeking the familial and
running characteristics that produced the most-successful
offspring. Working 16 hours a day for six months, he
identified 36 traits that seemed to count most, finding,
among other things, that the best racers usually had parents
who won fast races very early in their careers. Then he
backtested his program on the 26,129 horses that had been
offered for sale over a nine-year period at the four major
U.S. yearling sales.
   It gave a "yes" to just 433 animals, 1.7% of those
auctioned. Of those, 117 turned into stakes winners, about 10
times the proportion of the group as a whole.
   Other things about his program pleased him. "I wasn't only
identifying horses that sold for six figures and up; I found
the sleepers, too," he says. Among those were Spectacular
Bid, the $37,000 purchase who won the 1979 Derby, and Seattle
Slew, the '77 Triple Crown champ who'd been bought for a
bargain $17,500. Slew's "yes" sparked special delight because
he was Murphy's favorite horse. In celebration, he named his
company M375, which is "SLEW" spelled upside down and
backward.
   Murphy chucked the knuckler for the fastball and curve
that had made him a prospect, thus earning a "save" on his
baseball life, but pressed on with his equine endeavors.
Offering his services as an agent, he bought five horses for
a Seattle man, all of which posted wins, but clients declined
to take other recommendations that were to gain greater
glory. Frustration over such misfires led to his present
determination to oversee his own buying and racing
syndicates.
   Murphy lights up his computer almost everywhere, including
team flights, and has refined his program to encompass 55
traits. His tapping engendered some locker-room ribbing in
his early days in the Bigs, but now brings mostly requests to
invest. He says that a nice thing about being a ballplayer is
that it allows plenty of time for other activities. "The bus
for the park usually leaves about 4:30 p.m. If I get up at 9
a.m., I can put in a full day's work," he notes.
   Amazing what a guy can do if he doesn't watch cartoons,
isn't it?
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>
WSJ900504-0142
</DOCNO>
<DOCID>
900504-0142.
</DOCID>
<HL>
   Westcoast Energy Inc. Plans to Proceed
   With $429.2 Million Pipeline Expansion
   ----
   By Gary Lamphier
   Staff Reporter of The Wall Street Journal
</HL>
<DATE>
05/04/90
</DATE>
<SO>
WALL STREET JOURNAL (J), NO PAGE CITATION
</SO>
<CO>
   WE NPL+ WMB
</CO>
<IN>
PIPELINE OPERATORS (PIP)
MONETARY NEWS, FOREIGN EXCHANGE, TRADE (MON)
</IN>
<LP>
   VANCOUVER, British Columbia -- Westcoast Energy Inc. said
it expects to proceed with a 500 million Canadian dollar
(US$429.2 million) expansion of its pipeline system to
capitalize on a projected 60% jump in its natural gas exports
to the U.S. Pacific Northwest and California by the
mid-1990s.
   "We project that the Pacific Northwest and California will
require an additional 900 million to one billion cubic feet
of natural gas per day during the next five years," said
Michael Phelps, president and chief executive officer of
Westcoast, a pipeline, utility, and oil and gas concern.
</LP>
<TEXT>
   Mr. Phelps said he expects British Columbia producers, who
use Westcoast's 1,450-mile system to transport their gas from
the province's burgeoning gas fields, to supply about a third
of the additional U.S.-bound gas exports, or 300 million
cubic feet a day. That would add more than 60% to Westcoast's
1989 gas exports, or 475 million cubic feet a day.
   The exports accounted for more than 40% of Westcoast's
record-level daily volume last year of 1.13 billion cubic
feet, a 24% gain over 1988. The growth reflected the buoyant
economies of British Columbia and the U.S. Pacific Northwest,
and a growing appetite for natural gas.
   Arthur Willms, Westcoast's chief operating officer, said
its expansion spending would include about C$100 million to
boost capacity on its pipeline -- which interconnects with
Northwest Pipeline Corp.'s system at the Washington state
border -- and an additional C$400 million to expand gas
processing plants and gathering lines.
   Westcoast's upbeat export forecast hinges partly on an
expansion of Northwest's 6,500-mile system, which extends
from Washington's border with British Columbia, southeast to
New Mexico. In addition to its primary markets in Washington,
Oregon, and Idaho, the pipeline also serves Southern
California's growing gas markets, through an interconnection
with the El Paso natural gas pipeline.
   Northwest, a unit of Tulsa-based Williams Cos., is
discussing a possible expansion of its
two-billion-cubic-foot-a-day pipeline with gas producers and
expects to file an application this summer with U.S.
regulators.
   The size of the proposed expansion hasn't been decided,
said Tim Hausler, Northwest's vice president, marketing. But
he said any expansion would help Westcoast, which has
traditionally been locked into the Pacific Northwest market,
and unable to move gas to California, except on a spot basis.
   Certainly, Westcoast will face tough competition if it
hopes to win a slice of the California market.
   Several other large pipeline companies want a bigger piece
of the pie, including Pacific Gas &amp; Electric Co.'s pipeline
unit, which proposes a $1.2 billion expansion of its
Alberta-to-California pipeline.
   The proposal by San Fransisco-based Pacific Gas is
competing with the proposed $580 million Altamont pipeline,
sponsored by Houston-based Tenneco Inc., among others.
Altamont would run from Alberta to Wyoming, where it would
tie on to the proposed Kern River pipeline, which would
extend to California. Kern River is backed by Tenneco and
Williams.
   But analysts said it would be relatively cheap for
existing pipelines like Westcoast and Northwest to expand
their capacity, and Mr. Willms said Westcoast's spending
plans would have little impact on customer tolls.
   The proposals by Pacific Gas and Kern River's backers
would also complement Westcoast's aims, Mr. Phelps said,
because they would provide more direct routes to California,
via an expanded Northwest system.
   Northwest's line currently interconnects with the Pacific
Gas system, but the gas flows to Northwest, not to Pacific
Gas and on to California. Paula Rosput, a senior
vice-president with Pacific Gas's pipeline arm, said that
would change if the company's pipeline is expanded.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
