</DOCID>
<HL>
   Health Expenditures
   Rose 10.4% in 1988,
   Federal Agency Says
</HL>
<DATE>
05/04/90
</DATE>
<SO>
WALL STREET JOURNAL (J), NO PAGE CITATION
</SO>
<IN>
HEALTH CARE PROVIDERS, MEDICINE, DENTISTRY (HEA)
INSURANCE (INS)
</IN>
<GV>
HEALTH AND HUMAN SERVICES (HHS)
</GV>
<LP>
   WASHINGTON -- The nation's health expenditures rose 10.4%,
to $539.9 billion in 1988, the Department of Health and Human
Services said.
   The double-digit rise in 1988, the latest year for which
the department has figures, followed increases of 7.2% in
1986 and 8.5% in 1987. The acceleration primarily reflects a
faster rise in the general rate of inflation, an HHS
economist said.
</LP>
<TEXT>
   In 1988, health care accounted for 11.1% of gross national
product, the nation's total output of goods and services, up
from 5.9% in 1965, when the nation enacted two new federal
health programs -- Medicare for the elderly and Medicaid for
the poor.
   "Health care expenditures have been growing faster than
the national economy for many years," HHS Secretary Louis
Sullivan said in a statement. "This growth will strain the
ability of the American people to pay for quality health
care."
</TEXT>
</DOC>
