<HL>
   Oil Ministers
   Of OPEC Agree
   On Output Cuts
   ---
   Nearly 1.5 Million Barrels
   A Day to Be Trimmed;
   Markets Are Skeptical
   ----
   By James Tanner
   Staff Reporter of The Wall Street Journal
</HL>
<DATE>
05/04/90
</DATE>
<SO>
WALL STREET JOURNAL (J), PAGE A3
</SO>
<CO>
   MDEST
</CO>
<IN>
MONETARY NEWS, FOREIGN EXCHANGE, TRADE (MON)
PETROLEUM (PET)
</IN>
<LP>
   GENEVA -- OPEC's oil ministers pledged to cut their
combined output by nearly 1.5 million barrels a day in an
urgent effort to shore up sagging petroleum prices.
   If all 13 members of the Organization of Petroleum
Countries conscientiously honor their promises, they'd
essentially wipe out the full amount of OPEC's recent
over-ceiling production, which is blamed for most of the 25%
drop in world oil prices this year.
</LP>
<TEXT>
   Even if they don't, substantial compliance with the
unanimous agreement could at least ease the current oil glut.
   The development, nevertheless, was greeted with skepticism
in oil markets. Despite the fact that the mere scheduling of
the session had halted a worsening price slide in late April,
prices fell yesterday on reports of the agreement. The June
contract for West Texas Intermediate crude dropped 69 cents
to $17.99 a barrel on the New York Mercantile Exchange.
   The accord came early on the second day of the emergency
talks here, in keeping with the ministers' hopes for a
display of swift and decisive action. They have reasoned that
oil markets would be calmed by a brief and controversy-free
meeting. Ironically, the session was OPEC's first in some
time at which ministers had to address sharing output cuts,
rather than increases.
   Puzzled by the new price declines, the oil ministers still
held that their intent to reduce sharply the flow of oil
would eventually restore stability to volatile markets and
firm up prices.
   "Prices will definitely improve; I'm willing to put my
money on it," Ginandjar Kartasasmita, Indonesia's oil
minister, said in an interview.
   With the agreement calling for each country to make a
contribution, OPEC calculated the overall reduction at
1,445,000 barrels a day. That would bring production down to
22,055,000 barrels a day from April's estimated 23.5 million
barrels a day, and would make it about equal to the
organization's widely ignored first-half ceiling.
   The pledged cuts are effective for the months of May, June
and July. The idea is to remove enough oil -- at least one
million barrels a day -- from a glutted market to stabilize
prices until OPEC is beyond the current quarter, which has
been characterized by sluggish oil demand. During the third
quarter, world-wide use of petroleum generally begins to
rise.
   Pressure at the meeting for output reductions fell most
heavily on big overproducers such as Saudi Arabia, Kuwait and
the United Arab Emirates. Both Saudi Arabia and Kuwait
obligated themselves to cut back to their quotas of 5.4
million and 1.5 million barrels a day, respectively.
According to working figures used by other oil ministers in
calculating total reductions, that suggests cuts of 430,000
barrels a day for Saudi Arabia and 400,000 barrels a day for
Kuwait from recent actual rates.
   The United Arab Emirates, which had been flatly refusing
to recognize its quota in any manner, in effect rejoined OPEC
by agreeing to participate in the cutback plan. Mana Said
Otaiba, the UAE oil minister, told reporters: "We are
producing 2.1 million {barrels a day}. We promise to cut
200,000 {barrels a day}. So we will produce 1.9 million until
the end of July."
   Some questions arose about previous promises made by the
ministers of Kuwait and UAE, both chronic quota violators.
OPEC sources said Ali Khalifa Al-Sabah of Kuwait wouldn't
accept a cutback here unless the UAE dropped down at least
300,000 barrels a day and other overproducers also returned
to their quota limits.
   Mr. Otaiba was finally pushed to the point that he asked
his government for permission to cut, but only by 200,000
barrels.
   To salvage what seemed to be a shaky situation, Mr.
Ginandjar, the Indonesian minister, then proposed trimming
Indonesia's production by 40,000 barrels a day, even though
it isn't currently producing its full quota.
   Other volunteers also chipped in to help offset the UAE's
"missing" 100,000 barrels and satisfy Kuwait. At one time
during tense negotiations that went into the morning, the
Iranian and Iraqi ministers returned from a private
conference to offer cuts of 20,000 barrels a day each. Both
countries, like Indonesia, are also producing under-quota.
   "The principle is that everybody participates, no matter
how small," said OPEC's Secretary-General Subroto.
   The marketplace actually may have already accomplished
some of the cuts OPEC is counting. Members' sales of crude
oil recently have slackened, because buyers' storage
facilities are filled to their brims. By one estimate, OPEC's
output already has dropped as much as 500,000 barrels a day
from April's 23.5 million average.
   Still, some ministers suggested that "real" cuts of around
one million barrels a day would soon be evident in the oil
markets. "That should be enough," said one.
   Sadek Boussena, Algeria's oil minister and acting OPEC
president, disclosed that OPEC's next ministerial conference
was postponed to July 25 from a June date. At that meeting,
OPEC will determine production levels and country quotas for
the remainder of the year. By then, he said, demand for
OPEC's oil should be increasing again. "Some forecasts are
that it could be at least 24 million {barrels a day} in the
fourth quarter," he said.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>
WSJ900504-0067
</DOCNO>
<DOCID>
900504-0067.
</DOCID>
<HL>
   Credit Markets:
   Bond Prices Gain as Traders Cover Short Sales;
   Yield on 30-Year Treasury Issue Falls Below 9%
   ----
   By Constance Mitchell and Susan Scherreik
   Staff Reporters of The Wall Street Journal
</HL>
<DATE>
05/04/90
</DATE>
<SO>
WALL STREET JOURNAL (J), PAGE C19
</SO>
<CO>
   MER EUROP X.PAH HENG FRE
</CO>
<IN>
CDS, INTEREST RATES, COMMERCIAL PAPER (FIN)
BOND MARKET NEWS (BON)
MORTGAGES, MORTGAGE BANKERS, MORTGAGE-BACKED SECURITIES (MOR)
</IN>
<GV>
TREASURY DEPARTMENT (TRE)
FEDERAL GOVERNMENT (FDL)
</GV>
<LP>
   NEW YORK -- Traders pushed bond prices moderately higher
as they rushed to cover short-sale positions ahead of today's
potentially market-moving employment report.
   The Treasury's benchmark 30-year bond ended nearly 1/2
point higher, a gain of about $5 for a bond with a $1,000
face amount. The issue's yield, which moves in the opposite
direction of its price, slipped below 9% and finished at
8.97%.
</LP>
<TEXT>
   Municipal bonds, mortgage-backed securities and high-grade
corporate bonds ended as much as 1/2 point higher. Most junk
bonds were unchanged.
   Institutional investors remained on the sidelines, which
is typical prior to the release of the employment report.
   But dealers and speculators were active buyers as they
moved quickly to unwind money-losing short positions. In a
short sale, dealers sell borrowed securities and later seek
to make a profit by replacing what was borrowed with cheaper
securities. Essentially, these dealers are betting that
prices will fall.
   Many short positions were placed early Wednesday, on
speculation that bond prices would fall after the Treasury
announced details of next week's quarterly refunding, where
the government will sell $30.5 billion of securities. But
when bond prices rose instead, they were forced to enter the
market to buy bonds at higher prices.
   Analysts said another reason for the dealers cashing out
their short positions was fear that the employment report
will have a positive impact on the bond market and cause
prices to rise even higher.
   Although economists surveyed by Dow Jones Capital Markets
Report believe nonfarm employment rose a strong 384,000 last
month, the increase was distorted by an estimated 211,000
census workers, according to the economists. The unemployment
rate is expected to be unchanged at 5.2%.
   Statistics in line with expectations shouldn't have much
impact on bond prices. But the jobs data, considered one of
the most important of the monthly economic releases, are
difficult to predict, and surprises often jar the bond
market. The April statistics are seen as especially
significant because they are likely to set the tone at next
week's Treasury refunding.
   Meanwhile, the federal funds rate again drifted below the
Federal Reserve's target rate of 8 1/4%. The funds rate,
which banks charge each other on overnight loans, is closely
watched by analysts because the Fed often uses it to signal
changes in credit policy. But the rate sometimes moves for
technical reasons.
   In recent days, the rate has fallen under 8% because of
technical factors related to commercial banking matters. The
rate was 8 1/8% for most of yesterday.
   Typically, such weakness in the rate would prompt the Fed
to drain reserves from the banking system in an effort to
push the rate up to its target level.
   Some economists said the Fed didn't push the rate higher
because it didn't want to raise speculation that it is in the
process of tightening monetary policy. Others, however, said
the funds rate is expected to rise above the target level in
the next day or two as tax-related payments flow out of the
banking system. Therefore, they said, the Fed doesn't want to
drain reserves it will soon need to replace.
                                                                                                       

   Treasury Securities
                                                                                                       

   Treasury notes and bonds ended as much as 1/2 point
higher. The benchmark 30-year bond ended at a price of 95
1/32 to yield 8.97%, compared with a price of 94 19/32 to
yield 9.01% on Wednesday. The latest 10-year notes ended at
96 21/32 to yield 9%, compared with 96 10/32 to yield 9.05%
on Wednesday.
   Short-term rates eased slightly. The discount rate on
three-month Treasury bills fell to 7.86% for a
bond-equivalent yield of 8.11%, while the rate on six-month
bills fell to 7.98% for a bond-equivalent yield of 8.41%.
   The government sold $10 billion of 52-week Treasury bills
at an average discount rate of 8.05%. That was much higher
than the average rate of 7.72% at the previous 52-week bill
auction April 5 and was the highest average rate at an
auction since 8.18% on June 1, 1989.
   Here are auction details:
                                                                                                       

   Rates are determined by the difference between the
purchase price and face value. Thus, higher bidding narrows
the investor's return while lower bidding widens it. The
percentage rates are calculated on a 360-day year, while the
coupon-equivalent yield is based on a 365-day year.
                                                                                                       

                                          52-Week Bills

   Applications .......................  $30,408,160,000
   Accepted bids ......................  $10,035,740,000
   Accepted at low price ..............              93%
   Accepted noncompetitively ..........   $1,067,725,000
   Average price (Rate) ...............   91.861 (8.05%)
   High price (Rate) ..................   91.871 (8.04%)
   Low price (Rate) ...................   91.861 (8.05%)
   Coupon equivalent ..................            8.70%
                                                                                                       

   The bills are dated May 10 and mature May 9, 1991.
                                                                                                       

   Junk Bonds
                                                                                                       

   Following several days of brisk trading, the junk bond
market was quiet.
   The only exception was the bonds of PA Holdings Corp.,
which started to rise Wednesday on news that Henley Group
Inc. plans to spin off its two biggest units, Fisher
Scientific Group Inc. and Pneumo Abex Corp., in tax-free
distributions.
   PA Holdings' 13 3/4% senior subordinated notes due in 1999
gained five points to close at 75, while its 12 3/4% senior
extendible notes were bid five points higher at 95. The
securities represent bonds issued on behalf of Pneumo Abex.
   Henley Group Chairman Michael Dingman said that before the
spinoff, Henley will take a number of steps to inject equity
and remove debt from the units.
   Those steps to "de-leverage" the units, he said, would
make them viable companies and would boost the value of
Pneumo's junk bonds outstanding.
   Traders said activity was muted, in part, because some
investors wound down operations for the week as they headed
to Morgan Stanley &amp; Co.'s annual high-yield conference, which
began last night in Phoenix, Ariz.
                                                                                                       

   Mortgage-Backed Securities
                                                                                                       

   Bolstered by another big day of derivative mortgage-backed
issuance, active mortgage issues gained 11/32 to 3/8 point
and matched the advance in the intermediate Treasury market.
   There were $2 billion of real estate mortgage investment
conduits offered in five offerings, following the $2.2
billion announced Tuesday.
   The heavy Remic issuance reflects continued investor
demand for mortgage securities, which carry relatively high
yields and top credit ratings.
   Dealers noted that there recently has been a very light
supply of corporate bonds, a traditional alternative to
mortgage securities for many institutional investors.
   The lack of corporates has meant that institutions with
money to invest have had little choice but to buy Treasurys
or mortgage securities. Because mortgage securities yield on
average about one percentage point more than Treasurys,
mortgages have been the focus of strong demand.
   Traders said the demand for derivative mortgage securities
doesn't appear to be diminished by rumors that the office of
the Comptroller of the Currency soon will issue regulations
clamping down on bank purchases of risky derivative mortgage
issues.
   Government National Mortgage Association 9% securities for
May delivery ended at 93 3/4, up 3/8, and Federal Home Loan
Mortgage Corp. 9 1/2% securities were at 96 9/32, up 11/32.
   The Ginnie Mae 9% issue was yielding 10.06% to a 12-year
average life assumption, as the spread above the Treasury
10year note narrowed 0.01 percentage point to 1.06.
                                                                                                       

   Municipals
                                                                                                       

   Municipal bonds were up as much as 1/2 point, amid stifled
trading activity.
   "It's torture sitting here doing nothing," one New York
trader said, adding that trading was sparse and few
bid-wanted lists were visible in the market.
   In negotiated dealings, a Shearson Lehman Hutton Inc.
group priced $67.3 million of Ohio Water Development
Authority Series A and Ohio Air Quality Development Authority
Series B State of Ohio collateralized pollution control
revenue refunding bonds on behalf of the Toledo Edison Co.
Project.
   Also in the negotiated sector, the pricing of $158 million
of District of Columbia general obligation bonds has been
rescheduled to next week, said an official with lead
underwriter R.W. Corby &amp; Co.
   No large competitive issues were priced.
   Among active bonds, New Jersey Turnpike Authority's 7.20%
issue of 2018 was up 1/4 at 95 1/4 bid to yield 7.60%.
                                                                                                       

   Foreign Bonds
                                                                                                       

   Merrill Lynch &amp; Co. launched the first mark-denominated
zero-coupon bond the West German market has seen in 2 1/2
years. Merrill offered 100 million marks ($59.4 million) of
10-year securities that were priced at 43 3/4 to yield 9.26%.
The securities are non-callable.
   Rival syndicate houses said the issue was "too tightly
priced," meaning the yield was low relative to government and
quasi-government bonds that are used as market benchmarks.
One trader, for example, noted that a top-quality World Bank
issue yields 9.08%, only 0.18 percentage point less than the
Merrill issue.
   An investment manager said the Merrill Lynch issue is
unattractive at a time when investors still fear higher
interest rates, but Merrill officials said the issue was
prompted by demand from West German retail customers.
   Zero-coupon bonds pay no interest but are issued at a deep
discount. Investors' gains come from the difference between
the discounted purchase price and the face value received at
maturity.
   In trading yesterday, West German government bonds rallied
on news that the Bundesbank would leave interest rates
unchanged for the time being.
   But many analysts remain bearish about the market's
long-term prospects. And many economists believe that the
Bundesbank will eventually tighten monetary policy, possibly
in July.
   Bonn's 7 3/4% bond due 2000 rose 0.30 point to 93.25 to
yield 8.80%, while the 8% notes due in 1995 were up 0.13
point to 95.85 to yield 9.09%.
   In Britain, bond prices jumped as technical analysts told
customers the market was ready to rally.
   The Treasury's benchmark 11 3/4% bond due 2003/2007 rose
one point to 95 18/32 to yield 12.37%, while the 12% notes
due in 1995 rose 1/2 point to 95 5/32 to yield 13.38%.
   Japanese financial markets were closed yesterday in
observance of Constitution Memorial Day, and they will remain
closed today for Children's Day.
</TEXT>
