   Business Brief -- Reliance Group Holdings Inc.:
   First-Period Net Fell 64%
   On Revenue Increase of 8%
</HL>
<DATE>
05/04/90
</DATE>
<SO>
WALL STREET JOURNAL (J), NO PAGE CITATION
</SO>
<CO>
   REL
</CO>
<IN>
EARNINGS (ERN)
</IN>
<LP>
   Reliance Group Holdings Inc. said earnings declined 64% in
the first quarter primarily because of "difficult market
conditions in some lines of business."
   Profit fell to $9.6 million, or 13 cents a share, from
$27.1 million, or 36 cents a share, a year earlier. Revenue
rose 8% to $924.7 million from $854.9 million.
</LP>
<TEXT>
   Profit from property and casualty insurance operations
dropped 66% to $22.7 million from $67 million. New York-based
Reliance blamed price competition and a decline in premiums
written in 1990. However, income from life insurance as well
as title and mortgage insurance rose.
   Reliance has reported that its $630 million sale of its
General Casualty Insurance Co. subsidiary will result in a
$380 million pretax gain in the second quarter.
   In New York Stock Exchange composite trading yesterday,
Reliance closed at $5.625 a share, down 12.5 cents.
