900504-0039.
</DOCID>
<HL>
   Marketing Brief -- Washington Post Co.:
   First-Quarter Net Drops 6%,
   Hurt by Advertising Slump
</HL>
<DATE>
05/04/90
</DATE>
<SO>
WALL STREET JOURNAL (J), PAGE B5
</SO>
<CO>
   WPO
</CO>
<IN>
EARNINGS (ERN)
MEDIA, PUBLISHING, BROADCASTING, ELECTRONIC PUBLISHING (MED)
</IN>
<LP>
   Washington Post Co. posted a 6% drop in first-quarter net
income, hurt by the nationwide slump in newspaper
advertising.
   The results were slightly worse than analysts had
expected. Net fell to $39 million, or $3.16 a share, from
$41.5 million, or $3.22 a share. Analysts had expected
per-share earnings from $3.25 to $3.30.
</LP>
<TEXT>
   Sales dropped slightly to $341 million from $341.9
million. At the Washington Post, the flagship paper that
provides more than half of the company's total revenue, ad
linage dropped 6%, although higher ad rates kept revenue
flat.
   At Newsweek magazine, the second-largest source of company
revenue, sales declined 5% as ad pages fell 14%. Revenue at
the broadcast division dropped 8%. But cable revenue rose
11%, while revenue from Kaplan Educational Center was up 17%.
The company doesn't disclose earnings of the individiual
divisions.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
