900504-0008.
</DOCID>
<HL>
   Thrift Agency Seeks
   To Cut Costs, Weighs
   Consolidating Offices
</HL>
<DATE>
05/04/90
</DATE>
<SO>
WALL STREET JOURNAL (J), PAGE C16
</SO>
<CO>
   AMC
</CO>
<IN>
SAVINGS AND LOANS, THRIFTS, CREDIT UNIONS (SAL)
BANKS (BNK)
BANKRUPTCIES (BCY)
</IN>
<GV>
FEDERAL GOVERNMENT (FDL)
</GV>
<LP>
   WASHINGTON -- The Office of Thrift Supervision is
considering scaling back its extensive bureaucracy, including
possibly paring down its regional presence to mirror that of
banking regulators.
   The agency said that one of its highest priorities under
its new director, Timothy Ryan, will be cutting costs. The
office is examining, among other possibilities, trimming its
12 regional offices to five, in the same six cities where the
Comptroller of the Currency has offices. The comptroller
regulates federally chartered banks.
</LP>
<TEXT>
   Pending legislation would combine the thrift and banking
regulators; the moves proposed yesterday could be a prelude
to such a merger.
   Not surprisingly, the thrift industry favors reducing its
regulatory costs. Banks and thrifts pay their regulators a
fee, based on their sizes, to cover the cost of examinations.
"The cost per institution, as opposed to the Comptroller's,
is extraordinarily high," said James Grohl of the U.S. League
of Savings Institutions. According to the trade group, the
S&amp;L regulatory costs are more than double that of banks.
   The trade group opposes combining the banking and thrift
regulatory apparatus, however.
   The thrift office also proposed a regulation yesterday to
ban the sale of debt securities in S&amp;L offices. The proposal
is primarily in reaction to sales of bonds issued by
Phoenix-based American Continental Corp. at its Lincoln
Savings &amp; Loan Association subsidiary. Some holders of $200
million in now-worthless debt have testified before Congress
that they believed they were buying insured certificates of
deposit at Lincoln, in Irvine, Calif.
   The agency is seeking public comment on the proposals and
expects to have a decision by mid-June.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>
WSJ900504-0007
</DOCNO>
<DOCID>
900504-0007.
</DOCID>
<HL>
   East German Market
   Open to All Members
   Of EC, Says Minister
</HL>
<DATE>
05/04/90
</DATE>
<SO>
WALL STREET JOURNAL (J), NO PAGE CITATION
</SO>
<CO>
   EUROP
</CO>
<IN>
INTERNATIONAL ECONOMIC NEWS AND STATISTICS (IEN)
</IN>
<LP>
   BONN -- Economics Minister Helmut Haussmann, trying to
ease fears among other European Community members, said
Thursday that all EC countries should have the same
opportunities as West Germany in developing the East German
market.
   Mr. Haussmann said Bonn is advising the East German
government to provide tax incentives not only to West German
companies wanting to do business there, but also to all
interested companies.
</LP>
<TEXT>
   He pointed out that the planned German monetary and
economic union will open up great opportunities for foreign
industry. "From July onwards, every company that's active in
West Germany can also become active in East Germany," he
said.
   The freedom of competition in East Germany was a source of
concern expressed by some EC leaders at their Dublin summit
meeting Saturday.
   Mr. Haussmann said he had reached agreement with EC
officials that in the current first phase of German
unification, the EC wouldn't have any powers to veto or limit
aspects of continuing negotiations between the two countries.
   Regarding reconstruction of the East German economy, Mr.
Haussmann stressed the need to speed up plans to
denationalize the country's state-owned industries, but he
admitted that many details remain to be worked out. He said
privatization is essential to cope with a large number of
unemployed expected to result from the planned July 1
introduction of the Deutsche mark in East Germany.
   One problem in a large-scale privatization is the
impossibility to set an attractive price for key industrial
properties, because asset value is extremely limited. "And of
course, the earnings value of many big companies is small,"
said State Secretary Dieter von Wuerzen.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>
WSJ900504-0006
</DOCNO>
